10 Best Part-time Jobs for International Students in Canada!

  • 169 Reads
  • 3 min Read
  • By:CANAM Group
  • Updated On:Jun 27,2023 05:45 PM IST

Are you looking for the highest-paying part-time jobs in Canada? Part-time jobs help students in offsetting expenses and develop new skills. Read further to know about the best part-time jobs for international students in Canada.

Table of Contents

  • • Highest-Paying Part-Time Jobs for International Students in Canada
  • • Eligibility Criteria for Part-time Jobs in Canada
  • • Rules and Regulations for Student Work in Canada
Read More


Canada is one of the most popular study abroad destinations for international students. Besides offering a vibrant cultural experience, it also provides part-time employment opportunities which help students offset their tuition and living expenses. A part-time job can provide a much-needed additional source of income, as studying in Canada can be expensive. Students also learn how to manage their finances in a foreign country and contribute to skill development.

Highest-Paying Part-Time Jobs for International Students in Canada

Let's have a look at some of the highest-paying part-time jobs for international students in Canada.

Bookkeeper
Freelancer
Writer / Editor
Ride-sharing driver/delivery driver
Tutor
Teacher Assistant
Dog walker
Barista
Sales assistant
Server/bartender

Bookkeeper: A bookkeeper records and manages a company's financial transactions, including sales, purchases, income, and payments, ensuring accuracy and compliance with financial regulations.

Freelancer: A self-employed professional is a freelancer, who provides services to multiple clients working at home. They operate independently, choosing when, where, and how to work, and they typically get paid per project or task.

Writer/Editor: A writer/editor creates or edits written content for books, social media pages, articles, and blogs. They are involved in the entire writing process, ensuring clarity, correctness, and engagement.

Ride-Sharing Driver/Delivery Driver: Driving one's own car is required for this job to deliver packages or transport passengers. These drivers work in the gig economy and utilise apps like Uber, Lyft, and DoorDash.

Tutor: A tutor offers personalised, one-on-one educational assistance to students outside a traditional classroom setting. They help enhance understanding subjects, improve academic performance, and build learning skills.

Teacher Assistant: A teacher assistant supports the lead teacher by aiding with classroom management, assignments, lesson preparation, and providing individualised attention to students. They play a crucial role in creating a conducive learning environment.

Dog Walker: A dog walker provides exercise and care services for dogs while their owners are away or busy. They are in charge of ensuring the dogs' security while out on walks and frequently offer extra services like feeding or basic grooming.

Barista: A barista prepares and serves coffee and other beverages in a coffee shop setting. They have specialised knowledge about different types of coffee and brewing methods and often handle customer service and cash register duties.

Sales Assistant: A sales assistant supports the sales team by managing customer inquiries, processing transactions, and maintaining store aesthetics. They help in delivering a positive customer experience and help boost sales.

Server/Bartender: A server/bartender takes orders, serves food and beverages, and manages transactions in a restaurant or a bar setting. They ensure customer satisfaction through good service while adhering to food and beverage regulations.

Eligibility Criteria for Part-time Jobs in Canada

An international student must have a Social Insurance Number (SIN) and a valid study permit to work part-time in Canada. They must be enrolled as full-time post-secondary student at a recognised institution in order to work on campus.

For off-campus jobs, students must be enrolled as full-time students at a Designated Learning Institution (DLI) in a program that is at least six months long and leads to a degree, diploma, or certificate.

Rules and Regulations for Student Work in Canada

International students are permitted to work as many hours as they want on- campus, but they can only work off-campus for 20 hours per week during school terms. During semester breaks, they can work full-time. However, they must be a full-time student before and after the semester break.

Part-time jobs are an important part of an international student's journey in Canada. They not only provide financial support, work experience, skill development but also offers opportunities to network for a successful career. One must begin early to explore different and high paying part-time jobs in Canada. If you are interested to study in Canada or have any queries related to studying abroad, connect with Canam today! FAQ

What is a Social Insurance Number (SIN)?
A Social Insurance Number (SIN) is a nine-digit number provided by the Government of Canada that is required to work and access government programs and benefits in Canada.
How can international students locate part-time job opportunities in Canada?
International students can look for part-time jobs through online job portals, bulletin boards, social media, universities' career centers, networking, and local newspapers.
What are the different types of part-time jobs in Canada for international students in Canada?
International students can apply for different on-campus and off-campus part-time jobs in Canada.
What is the pay scale for Part-time Jobs in Canada?
Pay scale depends upon the type of work and job location. The average wage for part-time jobs is around CAD 22.50 per hour, with a minimum wage of CAD 11.45 per hour.
Are part-time jobs easily available for international students in Canada?
Yes, part-time jobs are easily available in Canada for international students. There is a lot of scope to work part-time both on-campus and off-campus.
How many hours can an international student work per week?
International students can work 20 hours per week off-campus during school terms.
What is the minimum Canada part-time jobs wage for international students?
The minimum part-time wage in Canada for students is CAD 10 per hour.
Which are the best jobs in Canada for students?
The best jobs in Canada for students are - teacher's assistant, tutor, waiter, bartender, or server, driver, freelancer, translator, salesperson, babysitter, and dog walker.
